@node "News" "What's new"


@{b}What's new since version 1.1@{ub}




Added Polish localization,  thanks to Jacek Rzeuski.

Fixed a bug the could lead to system hangs when the "auto update" feature was
used together with Miami.

You can now adjust separately the PPC and 68K priority for each client. Of
course the PPC priority doesn't have any effect on a 68K client. Recommended
values are:

    68K client: 68K priority = -120, niceness = 2, PPC priority not used
    PPC client: 68K priority = 1, PPC priority = -120, niceness not used

However, please note that adjusting the PPC priority can cause some problem, see
@{"bugs" link "Bugs" 0} for details.

Myzar windows are not selected anymore at startup

Since a lot of people complained about Myzar writing its stats to Envarc: (which
for example prevents turning off the hard drive at night), I've added the
tooltype STATSDIR, used to specify the directory where Myzar stores its
statistics files.

You can now query all client status values via AREXX using the flexible command
EXPAND: it converts a keyword into its value, more  of it @{"here" link "Arexx" 0}. Also added some
minor Arexx commands: ONLINE, OFFLINE, RUNBUFFERS, TOGGLEWINDOW, TOGGLESTATS.
@endnode

@node "rc5 challenge" "The RC5 Challenge"


@{b}About the RC5-DES challenge@{ub}


If you don't know what a RC5-DES client is, then you probably don't need this
program now. But you might need it later, just read on.

Have you ever asked yourself, looking at your Amiga doing nothing, "There must
be something I can do to use all that wasted CPU cycles."? Well, now you have
found a way to employ your spare CPU-time for something useful for the Amiga.

RC5 and DES are two encryption algorithms, in other words they are two methods
of encoding a byte sequence (e.g. a message of a file) so that only those who
have the appropriate key can decode it. These algorithm are widely used,
expecially in transactions over the Internet. In 1998 RSA-Labs proposed a
challenge: 10,000 dollars to those who are able to decrunch a message encrypted
with a 64-bit RC5 key, without having the key, of course. The only possible
method is by trying ALL the 2^64 possible keys (a 20-digits number). The
challenge was taken by Bovine and distributed.net: since this task is impossible
even for the fastest computer, they chose another approach: dividing the key
space (i.e the numbers from 0 to 2^64-1) into a huge quantity of sub-spaces
known as "blocks", and distributing these blocks to people who requested them.
People can use their computers to try all keys within their blocks, and send the
result to a main sever. To do that Bovine wrote a special software, able to ask
for blocks to the main server via the Internet, process those blocks and send
the results. Thise piece of software is an RC5 client. Currently clients are
available for almost every platform, including Amiga.

DES challenge is similar, but envolves a message encrypted with a 56-bit DES
key.

People envolved into this challenge are organized into groups, and the server at
distributed.net keeps track of all block processed and each day writes down a
classification. The Amiga RC5 Team is one of those groups: we are currently
employing more than 1000 people and we are ranked sixth, out of 60.000 between
groups and individual people involved. Since the RC5 challenge is bound to last
for years, YOUR contribution can be very useful.


To learn more about it all, you can have a look at the following URLs:

distributed.net: http://www.distributed.net

current statistics and classification: http://rc5stats.distributed.net


And don't forget the Amiga RC5 Team page: here you can find all information you
need to start giving your contribution NOW:

   http://distributed.amiga.org


After you have read it all (it is IMPORTANT that you read it all), you can learn
something about the amiga client @{"here" link "About client" 0}.
@endnode

@node "About client" "About the client"


@{b}About the client@{ub}



The RC5-DES client normally runs in a shell. It uses two buffers: one contains
blocks ready to be processed (the buff-in file), the other the already processed
blocks, which must be sent back to the server. There are actually two of both
buffers, for RC5 and DES blocks.

@{u}Network operations@{uu}

When the input buffer is empty, the client needs to downloads new blocks from
the net: this operation is known as "@{b}fetch@{ub}". The operation of sending processed
blocks back to the server to be included in the stats (and occasionally to
report that you have found the right key :) is known as "@{b}flush@{ub}". The client can
do both fetch and flush: in this case we talk about "@{b}update@{ub}". With Myzar, you
can force these operations manually via menu, see @{"usage" link "Usage" 0}.

@{u}Run modes@{uu}

The RC5 client was designed to run on machines always conncted to the Internet,
so by defaults it assumes it can fetch and flush blocks at will. This is the
default "@{b}online run mode@{ub}". There is also an "@{b}offline run mode@{ub}": the client will
never assume it is connected, and if it runs out of blocks it will generate
random ones. Another option is "@{b}run buffers@{ub}": the client will quit after the
last block is completed. Myzar allows you to switch between run modes using a
menu, but you normally don't need to change run mode very often. You will
probably set the default run mode (see @{"programáconfiguration" link "Config" 0}) either to "online"
if your Amiga is always connected to the Internet, or to "offline". In the
latter case you would fetch/flush blocks manually via the network menu, or have
Myzar do it automatically upon connection, see program @{"configuration" link "Config" 0}.


The status of your buffers is written in the client output, shown in the main
window listview, and summed up in the small window.

Now it is a good thing to see the chapter about @{"clientáconfiguration" link "Client config" 0}
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"


@{b}Requirements@{ub}



To run Myzar, you need:


    - An Amiga :)

    - Operating System version 3.0 or later (may work on 2.04)

    - Magic User Interface. It was only tested with version 3.8, but can work
      with previous versions as well.

    - The RC5-DES client. Currently version 2.7100.413 is mainly supported,
      but Myzar works with v2.7021.405 too. Please note that using that older
      version you will miss some (minor) features.

    - The PIPE: device must be mounted.

    - Miami or AmiTCP. They are not absolutely required, but it is needed to
      fetch/flush blocks automatically. Please note that AmiTCP support is
      experimental, and may not work correctly.



Since version 1.0, PPC users can run both PPC and 68K clients by running two
copies of Myzar (look @{"here" link "Twizar" 0} for details).
@endnode

@node "Install" "Installation"


@{b}Installation@{ub}



To install Myzar, just drag its drawer wherever you like.

If you want to have Myzar (and thus the RC5-DES client) automatically started
when system boots up, the best thing to do is to copy a project icon to your
WBstartup drawer on your SYS: partition. Then change that icon's default tool to
make it point to Myzar's executable.

A couple of project icons ready for this purpose are shipped with Myzar, have a
look inside the "Icons" drawer.

Hopefully, in a near future an installer script will take care of all this
stuff.

PPC users who want to start Myzar twice just have to put two project icons (all
pointing to the same Myzar executable) to the WBStartup drawer.

Remember that the program can be started in iconified mode, see @{"configuration" link "Config" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Config" "Myzar Configuration"


@{b}Configuration@{ub}



To configure the program, just select "@{b}settings/Myzar config@{ub}" from the menu.
That will open a window, which is divided into four sections. To understand some
of these options basic knowledge about the @{"RC5-DESáclient" link "About client" 0} is required.

The only mandatory option to make Myzar work, if you already have the RC5-DES
client installed and properly configured, is "Client exe".


@{u}Global@{uu}

Contains the most important settings. 


    Client exe:  the client executable, usually named 'rc5des', with path.


    Stack size:  the client will be launched using this stack size


    Priority  :  the client will be started with this task priority. Actually,
                 two numbers can be entered here: the first one is the 68K
                 priority, while the sencond is the PPC priority. Their
                 meaning changes if current copy of Myzar is running a PPC or
                 a 68K client.

                 For 68K clients: the 68K priority is the only value of
                 interest, and will become client's task priority if (and only
                 if) 'niceness' is set to 2 (see @{"clientáconfiguration" link "Client config" 0}).
                 This is not a bug: the client program itself adjusts its
                 priority if niceness is other than 2.

                 For PPC clients: the 68K priority affects the 68K side of the
                 PPC task, i.e. the one responsible for I/O access and system
                 calls. Since the 68K side uses very little CPU time, and
                 since its responsiveness is extremely important for the PPC
                 task to run at full speed, I suggest to keep it at 1 (i.e.
                 higher than normal user programs). The PPC priority affects
                 the PPC side of the task: PPC tasks are scheduled by the PPC
                 kernel, so they need a priority value, too. This value should
                 be kept low, so that the client doesn't slow down any other
                 PPC task that might be running (i.e. Quake :).

                 To sum up, some reasonable values are:

                 68K client:  68K priority = -120, niceness = 2
                 PPC client:  68K priority = 1, PPC priority = -120

                 Please note that for technical reasons (a bug in ppc.library
                 v46.19) the PPC priority can't be adjusted immediately, or a
                 crash might happen. So Myzar actually changes the PPC client
                 priority to the selected value only 15 seconds after it has
                 been started, just to be sure. Even so this feature could
                 (rarely) lead to system hangs. Look @{"here" link "Bugs" 0} for details.



    When a connection is detected do:  defines program's behaviour when a
                 dial-up connection is detected. Setting this to other than
                 'nothing' can save you the hassle of manually fetching and/or
                 flushing blocks each time you go on-line.

            Nothing:     does nothing. :)

            Auto fetch:  fetches new blocks from server, then the client is
                         restarted.

            Auto flush:  flushes already cracked blocks to server, then the
                         client in restarted.

            Auto update: does both fetch & flush, then restarts the client.

            Switch to online: stops the client and restarts it in @{"onlineámode" link "About client" 0}.
                         This can be useful if your machine is connected to
                         the Internet for a lot of hours per day.
                         The client will send/fetch blocks when it needs, but
                         only if a connection is already present. Of course
                         if you are connected 24 hours per day you might
                         prefer to start the client directly in online mode.
                         This  emulates the 'lurk only' mode of the Win32
                         clients.


            When the connection drops, the program restarts the client in the
            previous @{"runámode" link "About client" 0}.

            @{b}NOTE@{ub}: Currently you must use Miami or AmiTCP for the
            program to be able to detect connections. Note also that AmiTCP
            support is experimental, and may not work. Please let me know if
            it worked for you.


    Check for connection every:  sets the number of seconds the program must
            wait before asking the TCP/IP stack if connected. A value of 0
            means 'never' and might save some (very little) cpu time.




@{u}Appearance@{uu}

Configures some aspects of the GUI.



    Appicon image:  the icon to be used as the iconified-state image. This
            defaults to the program's icon if started from WB.

    Appicon text: not yet available.


    Text lines to buffer: the size, in lines, of the review buffer which
            contains the client output, displayed in the listview of the main
            ('verbose') window.

    End of block command: an AmigaDOS command to execute whenever a block is
            completed. You can use it to e.g. play a sample. You can test the
            command immediately using the button on the right.  There is
            actually a 3 seconds delay between block completion and command
            execution. This has been introduced to minimize disk trashing.




@{u}Small Window@{uu}

Contains options to alter the look of the small window. Since most users will
use this window only, a lot of effort has been made to make it as configurable
as possible. Each item displayable in the small window is represented by its
name in the left listview. Clicking on a name will activate the gadgets to the
right, which will be filled according to item's settings. You many now alter
those settings at will:

    Visible:    if checked, the item is actually shown within the small
                window. Clear this checkmark for items you are not interested
                in, i.e. the DES gauge when there is no active DES contest.

    Text:       the text displayed inside the item. To make this text as
                informative as possible, you may put keywords in it: Myzar
                will replace those keywords with actual pieces of information
                about client status, and update them as soon as they change.
                Have a look @{"here" link "Keywords" 0} for a complete list of all available
                keywords.
                There is also a pop-up button on the right: pressing it brings
                up a list of all supported keywords with a short description
                or their meaning. Chosing a keyword from this list will add it
                to the text field.

    Font:       the font used for the item. It must be in the form
                <name>/<size> (e.g. topaz/8). The button on the right pops up
                a font requester to help you with selection.

    Bottom space: inserts some space at the botton of the selected item. The
                value is in pixels.


You may also alter items' order within the small window by sorting their names
in the left listview: just pick the names with the left mouse button and drag
them to their new position.


Two buttons are available:

    Test:       applies the changes you have made: if open, the small window
                will be closed and re-opened according to current settings.
                Use it to test any modification you have made.

    Defaults:   all items are reset to their internal defaults.



Items names should be self explainatory, just a couple of notes.

- From version 1.1 an "Extra text" item is present, use it to title the window
  or to put in some information about your CPU speed to impress friends. :)

- The "speed text" is of course not limited to speed data, you may use it for
  everything you like.

- You may not alter the "current block" text, since it is used by Myzar to
  display some extra information.




@{u}Startup@{uu}

Some program defaults and initial options.


    Client default run mode:  when Myzar is started, it launches the client
            in this mode.

    When launched open:  the @{"window" link "Usage" 0} to open at startup. Choose either
            'verbose' or 'small'.

    Start iconified:  if checked, the program will not open a window when
            started, but will appear as an icon on WB. You may open the window
            by double-clicking on this icon. This can be useful if you choose
            to put Myzar in the WBStartup drawer. The icon image is the same
            as the program icon, but can be changed (see 'appearance').


@{b}NOTE@{ub}: from version 1.0, the default run mode is "online". If you don't have a
permanent connection to the Internet, remember to change the default run mode to
either "offline" or "run buffers", otherwise the client will quit if no TCP/IP
stack is present.



At the bottom of this window there are the standard three buttons:

@{i}Save@{ui}: prefs are used immediately, and saved to both ENVARC: and ENV:,
               so that they survive reset.

@{i}Use@{ui}: prefs are used, but saved to ENV: only. Any possible
              modification will not survive a reset.

@{i}Cancel@{ui}: restores the previous configuration.


Note that changes in 'text lines to buffer' do not take effect immediately, but
only when the program is restarted.



If this is the first time you use an RC5-DES client, you should configure it as
well, see @{"clientáconfiguration" link "Client config" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Keywords" "Keywords"


@{b}Keywords@{ub}


The following keywords are recognised inside the text gadget of the small window
items, and expanded to their current values at run time:


    %rc5in   Number of blocks in the RC5 input buffer

    %rc5out  Number of blocks in the DES input buffer

    %desin   Number of blocks in the RC5 output buffer

    %desout  Number of blocks in the DES output buffer

    %maxrc5  Maximum number of blocks in the input buffer, as configured
             in @{"clientáconfig/client/maxáRC5áblocks" link "Client config" 53}.

    %maxdes  The same for DES blocks.

    %lstspd  Keyrate for the last calculated block

    %avgspd  Average keyrate since last stats reset

    %bstspd  Maximum keyrate since last stats reset

    %cpu     CPU the client is using for calculations (68K or PPC)

    %status  Current client status (running, idle..)

    %blktp   Type of the block currently being processed (RC5 o DES)

    %blkdn   Total number of 2^28 blocks completed since last stats reset

    %%       Just the % character


The EXPAND @{"Arexxácommand" link "Arexx" 0} can be used to query those values from Arexx scripts.
In this case you may pass them to Myzar without the trailing %, too.
@endnode

@node "Client config" "Client configuration"


@{b}Configuring the RC5-DES client@{ub}



To enter client configuration, select settings/client config... from the menu.


The window you are presented with is divided into four sections:


@{u}Global@{uu}

    Email address: enter you address here. This is required, so that the
                   server at distributed.net can update your stats and add
                   your blocks to the Amiga RC5 Team, if you  have configured
                   it so. Also, if you find the right key, this is the only way
                   to know that YOU did it. :)

    Max blocks:    for each contest, sets the number of blocks to keep in the
                   input buffer. When you @{"fetch" link "About client" 0}, the client will download
                   blocks until the number of blocks in the input buffers
                   equals this one. You have to enter a value here large
                   enough to make sure you don't usually run out of blocks,
                   but don't use large values unless you really need.

    Threshold:     the threshold value indicates when to @{"flush" link "About client" 0} blocks
                   automatically: if the client is in @{"on-lineámode" link "About client" 0} (and ONLY
                   if in on-line mode), when the number of blocks in the
                   output buffers equals this number, the client will connect
                   to the server and do an @{"update" link "About client" 0}. This setting should have no
                   effect if you use to run the client in @{"offline" link "About client" 0} or
                   @{"runbuffers" link "About client" 0} mode.

    Preferred block size: the client will ask the server for blocks of that
                   size (in bits), but note that the server can send smaller
                   blocks instead. It will take a 50 MHz 68060 about 45 minutes
                   to complete a 2^28 RC5 block, and this time will double
                   every unit in block size beyond 28. Thus a 2^30 block will
                   take 3 hours to complete. Using bigger block size can be
                   useful to lower transfer times, since it takes the same
                   time tu up-download a block of any size, but you need fewer
                   blocks. 2^30 blocks are counted in the stats as four 2^28
                   blocks, and so on.

    Blocks in Ram: forces the client to keep buffers in ram, thus reducing
                   disk I/O to the very minimum. BE VERY CAUTIOS WITH THIS
                   OPTION, since in case of crash you may loose all your
                   blocks!


@{u}Client@{uu}

    Preferred contest: you should normally set this to DES, since this allows
                    your client to automatically switch to DES blocks when a
                    DES contest starts (there are two per year), and to revert
                    back to RC5 blocks when it's finished. DES contests are
                    very quick (two weeks or less), so there is no reason not
                    to take part in them.

    Checkpoint files: those are files the client writes every some minutes to
                    mark progress within current block. It's highly
                    recommended to use those file for two reasons: if your
                    machine crashes you only lose some minutes' work, and,
                    most important, you don't lose the current block. Just
                    write two different filenames here, the default is
                    ckpoint.rc5 and ckpoint.des.

    Time:           tells the client how many minutes to wait before updating
                    the checkpoint files. In case a crash happens, you will
                    lose at most "time" minutes of work.


    Niceness:       since cracking RC5 blocks it's probably not the most
                    important thing you are doing with your Amiga, the client
                    must run at very low priority, so that it only uses CPU
                    cycles that are not needed by any other program. If you
                    set 0 or 1 here, the client will run at task priority -20
                    or -10 respectively. If you set 2, the client will run at
                    the priority defined in @{"Myzaráconfig/global" link "Config" 0}. This allows
                    to set even lower priorities.


@{u}Network@{uu}

    Proxy keyserver: the host to fetch/flush blocks to/from. Unless you
                    have good reason for changing it, leave it to the default
                    value.

    Proxy port:     the port to connect to.


@{u}Logging@{uu}

    Log file:       if you enter a filename here, all client operations will
                    be logged to that file. Type "none" to disable.

    Message Length: if non-zero will enable log mailing, i.e. when the client
                    has written "length" lines of log, those lines will be
                    sent as an e-mail message to the address provided (see
                    below). Useful if you want to see remotely what your Amiga
                    is doing. You don't need to use a log file for this to
                    work.

    SMTP server, port: the SMTP server and port the client will use to send
                    e-mail messages. Usually this will be your Internet
                    provider's SMTP server/port.

    Send to address: the e-mail address to send messages to.

    From address:   messages sent by the client will have this address in the
                    From: field, i.e. they will appear as sent from this
                    address.





Below there are three buttons:

@{i}Save@{ui}: save the settings to the client's .ini file. Those settings will take
      effect next time the client is started.

@{i}Save/restart@{ui}: saves the settings and restarts the client, to allow immediate
              effect.

@{i}Cancel@{ui}: drops any change you have made.


Note that there is no USE button, because there is no way to notify the client
that its configuration has changed.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"


@{b}Usage@{ub}

To run Myzar, just double click on its icon. Before trying Myzar's option is
important that you @{"configure" link "Config" 0} it. But if you already have the RC5 client up and
running, the only parameters you have to set before trying Myzar are those
included in @{"Myzaráconfiguration/global" link "Config" 15}. Remember to quit any running clients
before askin Myzar to start its own client instance.


Myzar has two modes of operation. The default one is with client's output
displayed in Myzar's "verbose window". There is not a big (visual) difference
between running Myzar in this mode and running the client in a shell, but you
can safely iconify the application, scroll the buffer back to see what happened
and use the menus to affect client's behaviour (e.g. to force an update).

If you are tired with client's output, you may try the "small window" instead.
It sums up useful information provided by the client and displays them in a much
more readable form. For example, the ugly ASCII progress bar now becomes a real
progress bar with percentage esplicitly shown. Furthermore, you can alter the
look of this small window to make it show only the information you are
interested in. You can toggle items displayed, change their order and the font
they use, and much more. See @{"configuration/smalláwindow" link "Config" 101} for details.

You can toggle between small and verbose window at any time using the "Windows"
menu.

@{"Tooltypes" link "Tooltypes" 0}         @{"ááMenusááá" link "Menus" 0}        @{"Arexxácommands" link "Arexx" 0}
@endnode

@node "Tooltypes" "Icon tooltypes"


@{b}Tooltypes@{ub}


Currently, only two tooltypes are supported:


NOAUTOSTART           Tells Myzar not to start the client automatically.

STATSDIR <directory>  If you specify a directory here, Myzar will save there
                      its statistics file instead of Envarc:. Useful if
                      you e.g. want to keep your hard drive off during night
                      and thus don't want Myzar to access the SYS: partition
                      each time a block is completed.


You can also specify them as parameters on the command line.
@endnode

@node "Menus" "Menu items"


@{b}Menus@{ub}




This sections describes menu items. Please note that you must @{"configure" link "Config" 0} the
program before using most of these items.



@{u}Project menu@{uu}

    Start:       launches the client in the selected @{"runámode" link "About client" 0}, if not already
                 working. Please note that during normal usage the client is
                 automatically launched at program startup (unless told not
                 to do so, see @{"tooltypes" link "Tooltypes" 0}). The client output is displayed in
                 the main window.

    Stop:        stops current client operation

    Benchmark:   tells the client to perform a speed benchmark.

    Test client: tells the client to perform a self test.

    About:       opens a small information window

    About MUI:   opens the standard MUI information window.

    Iconify:     iconifies the program.

    Quit:        stops the client and quits the program.



@{u}Settings menu@{uu}

    Myzar config...: opens the @{"Myzaráconfiguration" link "Config" 0} window.

    Client config..: opens the @{"clientáconfiguration" link "Client config" 0} window.

    MUI...         : opens the MUI configuration window.



@{u}Network menu@{uu}

    Fetch:  tells the client to fetch more blocks from the server. The client
            will try to replenish the input buffers, i.e. at the end of the
            operation the number of blocks in the input buffers will be equal
            to values specified as "max blocks" in client
            configuration/global.

    Flush:  tells the client to flush already cracked blocks to server

    Update: tells the client to perform both fetch and flush


For those items to work an Internet connection must be up. These operations can
be performed automatically when a connection is detected, see program
@{"configuration/global" link "Config" 15}.



@{u}Run mode menu@{uu}

Selects the client @{"runámode" link "About client" 0}. The default value for this menu can be set in
@{"programáconfiguration/startup" link "Config" 190} options.



@{u}Windows menu@{uu}

    Verbose/Small: Toggles between small and verbose @{"window" link "Usage" 0}. The window to
                   open at startup can be set in @{"programáconfiguration/startup" link "Config" 190}.

    Stats...     : Brings up the @{"statsáwindow" link "Stats" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Arexx" "Arexx commands"


@{b}Arexx commands@{ub}


Myzar has got an AREXX port which allows it to be controlled from scripts or
other programs. Supported commands are:

    START
    STOP
    UPDATE
    FETCH
    FLUSH
    ONLINE
    OFFLINE
    RUNBUFFERS

Those behave like the corresponding @{"menuáitems" link "Menus" 0}.


    TOGGLEWINDOW

Makes Myzar switch from verbose window to small window, and vice-versa


    TOGGLESTATS

Opens/closes the stats window.


    EXPAND  (STRING/A)

This is a powerful command. It is used to convert one of Myzar's keywords
(passed as a parameter of the EXPAND command) to its current value. Keywords are
the same you can use within text gadget of the small window (@{"here" link "Keywords" 0} is a list),
and get expanded exactly the same way. The only difference is that only one
keyword at time can be expanded, and that you can specify it without the trailin
"%", too. The Arexx variable RESULT will contain the converted string. This
command can be used from within your scripts to query some client parameters and
act accordingly. For example, you might wish to see if there are enough blocks
in the RC5 input buffer and in case do a fetch: here is what your script would
look like:

 /* get the number of rc5 blocks in output buffer */
 ADDRESS MYZAR.1
 OPTIONS results
 EXPAND 'rc5in'
 IF result < 5
 THEN FETCH




In addition there are some generic commands, common to all MUI applications:

    QUIT    forces Myzar to quit
    HIDE    tells Myzar to iconify itself
    SHOW    if iconified, re-opens Myzar's interface

Arexx ports are named MYZAR.1, MYZAR.2 and so on. If you launch two or more
copies of Myzar and don't remember their order, just select About from the
Project menu: you will find the Arexx  port name there.
@endnode

@node "Stats" "Stats window"


@{b}Stats window@{ub}



It is a small window containing some information about client activity over
time. The two menu items allow to reset the stats (after a confirmation) and to
save them as text.

The title indicates the date and time of day since which those statistics are
calculated.


    Days of activity:       it is simply the difference between the date of
                            last stats reset and current date. Time of day is
                            also taken into account.

    2^28 blocks completed:  number of blocks completed. Larger blocks count
                            more than smaller blocks, i.e. a 2^30 blocks counts
                            as four 2^28 blocks, an so on.

    Average blocks per day: easy to guess. :). Actually the numnber of days
                            here is calculated as a floating point number, so
                            this number can be different from the ratio of the
                            two numbers described above.

    Random blocks:          number of random blocks generated by the client.
                            Try to keep it low. :)

    Total keys processed:   total number of keys your client has tried, in
                            billions.

    Maximum keyrate:        the best keyrate your client has been able to keep
                            during an entire block.

    Average keyrate during activity: the average of keyrates reported by the
                            client (weighted by block size). Since this number
                            only depends of what the client reports, it
                            measures your average keyrate when the client is
                            running.

    Overall keyrate:        a global average also taking into account periods
                            of time when the client is NOT running (e.g
                            because your Amiga is turned off). It is
                            calculated by dividing number of keys by the number
                            of seconds from stats reset until present time,
                            and should describe your contribution to the
                            effort a bit better. That's because
                            distributed.net is interested in blocks per day
                            you actually do, not those you could have done
                            if your client was running 24/7.



This window can be kept open. In that case it is automatically refreshed some
seconds after a new block has been completed.

Please note that statistics are just that: statistics. That means that they
begin to show useful results only when you have run Myzar for a sufficiently
long period of time. When only a few blocks have been completed, results may
also be funny: for example the "overall keyrate" may excede the "maximum
keyrate". This is due to a partially completed block, whose contribution becomes
negligibly small after that some other blocks have been competed as well.

PLEASE DON'T FLAME ME if your statistics don't look correct at first, this is
only due to the small sample used to compute them.
@endnode

@node "Bugs" "Bugs & Future"


@{b}Bugs@{ub}


- Sometimes the PPC client can cause an exception of the kind "No taskobject
  active". If so, Myzar hangs and starts eating up al 68K CPU time. This is
  caused by a bug in the ppc.library V46.19 that sometimes Myzar exploits when
  changing the PPC priority of the PPC client. This should happen very rarely,
  and only during the first minute after the PPC client has started, so if the
  client runs fine for a minute, then it will not crash anymore. I couldn't
find
  a workaround for that, I'm sorry. However there is a solution: if Myzar
  hangs too often for you, just set the @{"PPCápriority" link "Config" 26} of the PPC task to 0. You
  will lose a feature, but that way the PPC client will never hang.

- When DES contest is on, the RC5 gauge shows nothing , and vice versa. This
  is because the client only shows data about one contest at time. There's
  nothing I can do about it.

- Some localizations may miss some shortcut, it's not translators' fault, it's
  mine. That will probably change in the next version.

- Myzar is unable to break its own client instance if another client with the
  same name is running. Unfortunately, this is caused by the client program
  itself, that can't be launched by CreateNewProc(). This can't be fixed
  until a better client is released.

- AmiTCP support may have some bugs, since I wasn't able to figure out a
  reliable way of detecting a connection.

- With clients that print a sequence of "<" and ">" when sending/receiving
  blocks (such as the PPC client v2.7100.413), the progress bar isn't always
  accurate during network activity. There is nothing I can do about it.

- Sometimes the "text" field in the small window configuration may retain a
  "ghosted" border, which disappears if yuo force the window to redraw (for
  example by resizing it). I think this one is a MUI bug, but it's harmless.

- This guide is a mess. :) If you have suggestions about how to improve it,
  I'll really appreciate them. Also, my English sucks. :)


There can be more bugs of course. If you found something not listed above,
please @{"letámeáknow" link "Author" 0}.




@{b}Future@{ub}


- Support for more TCP/IP stacks. If you need how to detect a connection with
  different stacks, please tell me.

- Support both PPC and 68K with one program only.

- "mooo after each block" feature (send me samples!). You can have something
  similar even now using the "execute command after each block" feature and
  some shell audio player like Play16.

- Improve localization

- Rework my dirty code a bit :)

- Anything you might suggest. Feel free to send @{"me" link "Author" 0} your ideas!
@endnode

