@node "History" "History"
@{b}History@{ub}




@{u}Version 1.11 (16-11-1998)@{uu}

- Added polish localization

- Fixed a bug the could lead to system hangs when the "auto update" feature
  was used together with Miami.

- You can now adjust separately the PPC and 68K priority for each client.

- fixed a small bug that resetted the progres bar when more that 127 blocks
  were fetched/flushed (hi Dave :)

- Myzar windows are not selected anymore at startup

- Added the tooltype STATSDIR, used to specify the directory where Myzar
  stores its statistics files. Default is ENVARC:.

- Added new Arexx commands EXPAND, ONLINE, OFFLINE, RUNBUFFERS, TOGGLEWINDOW,
  TOGGLESTATS.




@{u}Version 1.1 (03-10-1998)@{uu}

- Localized

- Small window much more configurable: you can change text, font and bottom
  space for each object, and rearrange them at will. Added a keyword parser to
  allow each object to show information about every area of client activity.

- Doesn't require "break" and "status" commands anymore.

- Speed format is now configurable (e.g. 123.2 KKeys/sec or 123244 Keys/sec).

- Myzar now saves useful information like number of blocks done, average
  speed, etc.

- Added a "stats window", updated after each block.




@{u}Version 1.0a (27-08-1998)@{uu}

- Fixed a bug that prevented from using absolute paths in client configuration
  (e.g. for log or checkpoint files).

- Added a three-seconds delay before command execution when a block is
  completed to minimize disk trashing.




@{u}Version 1.0 (02-08-1998)@{uu}

- Much faster refresh, should look good on AGA, too.

- More client options can be configured from within Myzar

- Now multiple instance are allowed, each one reading its preference file from
  env: (Myzar.1.config, Myzar.2.config....). It allows PPC users to start two
  copies of Myzar, one for each client.

- Users is now warned about random blocks and whenever the client stops

- Myzar now defaults to "online" mode

- Removed all unneeded FindPort()

- Myzar is now compatible with rc5des v2.7021.405, but it is still designed
  for version 2.7100.413.

- added the tooltype DONOTSTART to inhibit client auto-start.

- Experimental AmiTCP support.

- Added an indication about speed in small window

- You can now have Myzar run a specified command whenever a block is completed

- AREXX port



@{u}Version 0.9 (14-07-1998)@{uu}

First public release
@endnode

@node "Twizar" "Twizar"
               @{b}Twyzar (Using Myzar for both, 68K and PPC, RC5 clients)@{ub}

                 by Georg Rottlaender (Georg.Rottlaender@home.ivm.de)
 


@{u}Additional requirements@{uu}
 


Myzar v1.0 was succesfully  tested  running  both  AmigaOS  2.7100.413 clients
(68K/PPC) at once with the following configuration:

Hardware: A4000, CSPPC200/60/50, 2MB Chip, 112MB Fast, Piccolo 'Classic' ...

Software: Kickstart v40.68 (3.1), Workbench v40.42 (3.1), CyberGraphX 3,
          68060.library v44.5 and ppc.library v46.19 (Release: 11-07-98) ...

With this config the I/O redirection, required by Myzar, is fully functional.

I don't know if the I/O redirection will work as expected and required by Myzar
with prior versions of the PPC client or the ppc.library.

As the PPC client now uses the HUNKOBJ format, there's now need for any patches
(ELFLoadSeg, RunELF or even PPCInstall) to start the client directly or via
Myzar.






@{u}How to configure Myzar for two clients@{uu}



Before the configuration of Myzar for both clients  (68K/PPC)  it's  useful to
think about the sequence of configuration.

As - for the moment - the first copy of Myzar launched will load the first
configured prefs file (ENV:Myzar.1.Config), the second copy the second
configured prefs file (ENV:Myzar.2.Config) and so on, it's for example only
possible to launch the PPC client via one copy of Myzar, when it was the first
you configured or another copy was running before but closed after the start of
the second copy.

Having configured the PPC client via the second copy of Myzar means, that
running the PPC client always needs a running first copy of Myzar (configured
for 68K). The client doesn't have to work on cracking RC5, but the first copy of
Myzar has to be executed before.

I would recommend to start Myzar once to configure the first copy for the PPC
client as this is the client that's mostly running all the time.

After configuring the first copy (Do not close it before the second copy was
configured!) you have to start a second copy at the same time to configure Myzar
for example for the 68K client.
@endnode

@node "Faq" "Frequently Asked Questions"


@{b}Frequently Asked Questions@{ub}




Q: What's the difference between starting the client in online mode and using
   Myzar's "Auto update" feature?

A: If you start the client in online mode, it will try to connect to a
   remote server each time it needs to send or receive some blocks. This
   setting is recommended only if you have a permanent connection to the
   Internet, since if no connection is available the client would stop or lose
   time trying to connect to an unreachable server. On the other hand, if you
   activate Myzar's "Auto-update" feature, the client will normally run in
   offline mode and will never try to connect to the Internet, but will do an
   update (and only ONE update) whenever a connection is detected. You may of
   course choose to fetch or flush instead of update, but please remember that
   only one fetch/flush/update is done, while if you run the client in on-line
   mode it will try to connect whenever it needs to.



Q: What is the best run mode?

A: There is no best run mode, but you can stick to these simple rules:

   - Your Amiga is always connected: set Myzar to always start the client in
   online mode, and use low treshold values (client config/blocks).

   - Your Amiga is connected to the Internet for a lot of time, say, 6 or more
   hours per day: the best thing to do is to set the Max Blocks values so that
   the client never runs out of blocks during the longest periods of no
   connection, tell Myzar to "Switch to Online" when it detects a
   connection (see @{"Myzaráconfig/Global" link "Config" 0}) and set the default client run mode
   to "offline".

   - Your Amiga is rarely connected to the Internet, one-two connection per
   day or less: set the Max Blocks values to cover the longest periods of
   non-connection, and set the client default run mode to "Offline". Then set
   Myzar to "auto-update": this will save you the hassle of remembering to
   update manually whenever you go online.

   - You prefer to update manually: set "Myzar config/global/when a
   connection is detected do" to "Nothing" and "check for connection every" to
   0 seconds.



Q: Myzar does launch the client, but it stops immediately.

A: Either Myzar is trying to run the client in online mode and no TCP/IP
   stack is running, or you have the run mode set to "run buffers"
   and all blocks have been processed. Have a look at the status of the
   "Run mode" menu.



Q: I have a PPC board, how the hell can I use Myzar for both PPC and 68K
   clients?

A: Georg Rottlaender wrote an how-to on the topic, see @{"here" link "Twizar" 0}.



Q: I moved the "68k priority" slider to -128, but my 68K client still runs
   at a task priority of -20.

A: For the 68K priority slider to work with the 68K client you have to set
   client niceness to 2, see "@{"clientáconfiguration/client" link "Client config" 52}".



Q: Stats are wrong! I've done two blocks, and averages seems completely
   meaningless.

A: Two blocks, but even ten or twenty, are not a sample large enough to
   make useful statistics. When they seem to remain almost stable over time
   they also become meaningful. That may take days or weeks depending on CPU
   speed and on how long you run Myzar during a day. If you own a 68060 and
   run Myzar for 12 horus per day, stats should become stable after a week or
   so, while it may take several weeks on a 50 MHz 68030.



Q: Why are my average and overall keyrates so different?

A: You probably run Myzar only for a few hours a day, or you turn it off when
   doing heavy calculations. "Average keyrate during activity" and "Overall
   keyrate" are only identical if you run Myzar 24/7.



Q: Before making a network update Myzar said that current block was 70%
   complete, while now it says block is 0% complete. Have I lost my work?

A: Not at all. The client handles blocks in a stack-like fashion: newer blocks
   are always precessed first. So when you issued the update command, the
   client saved your partially completed block, and then added fetched blocks
   "on the top" of it. If pay attention, you will notice that the client will
   resume your block as soon as it has completed the ones it has just
   downloaded.



Q: By the way, what does "Myzar" mean?

A: Nothing, it just sounds good. :) Actually, there is a star named like that
   (but spelled "Mizar"), in the costallation of Ursa Maior: it and its
   companion Alcor form one of the most famous double stars in the sky.
@endnode

